<div id="Thmexercise1" class="ltx_theorem ltx_theorem_exercise">
<h6 class="ltx_title ltx_runin ltx_title_theorem"><span class="ltx_tag ltx_tag_theorem"><span class="ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Exercise 1</span></span> (Branching Process Tools).</h6>
<div id="Thmexercise1.p1" class="ltx_para">
<p class="ltx_p">Assume <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="X=(X_{n})_{n}" display="inline"><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow></math> are identically distributed, independent and
integrable random variables. And assume <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m2" class="ltx_Math" alttext="N" display="inline"><mi>N</mi></math> is an integrable <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m3" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\mathbb{N}_{0}" display="inline"><msub><mi>ℕ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math>-valued
random variable independent of <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m4" class="ltx_Math" alttext="X" display="inline"><mi>X</mi></math> and <math id="Thmexercise1.p1.m5" class="ltx_Math" alttext="S_{n}:=\sum_{k=1}^{n}X_{i}" display="inline"><mrow><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>:=</mo><mrow><msubsup><mo largeop="true" symmetric="true">∑</mo><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>n</mi></msubsup><msub><mi>X</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow></mrow></math>.</p>
<ol id="S0.I1" class="ltx_enumerate">
<li id="S0.I1.i1" class="ltx_item" style="list-style-type:none;"><span class="ltx_tag ltx_tag_item">1.</span> 
<div id="S0.I1.i1.p1" class="ltx_para">
<p class="ltx_p">(Wald’s equation) Prove that</p>
<table id="S0.EGx1" class="ltx_equationgroup ltx_eqn_align ltx_eqn_table">

<tbody id="S0.Ex1"><tr class="ltx_equation ltx_eqn_row ltx_align_baseline">
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padleft"></td>
<td class="ltx_td ltx_align_right ltx_eqn_cell"><math id="S0.Ex1.m1" class="ltx_Math" alttext="\displaystyle\mathbb{E}[S_{N}]=\mathbb{E}[N]\mathbb{E}[X_{1}]" display="inline"><mrow><mrow><mi>𝔼</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>N</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow></mrow><mo>=</mo><mrow><mi>𝔼</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>N</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow><mo>⁢</mo><mi>𝔼</mi><mo>⁢</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><msub><mi>X</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow></mrow></mrow></math></td>
<td class="ltx_eqn_cell ltx_eqn_center_padright"></td></tr></tbody>
</table>
</div>
<div id="Thmhintx1" class="ltx_theorem ltx_theorem_hint">
<h6 class="ltx_title ltx_runin ltx_title_theorem"><span class="ltx_tag ltx_tag_theorem"><span class="ltx_text ltx_font_bold">Hint</span></span>.</h6>
<div id="Thmhintx1.p1" class="ltx_para">
<p class="ltx_p"><span class="ltx_text ltx_font_italic">Use indicators and Fubini.</span></p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="ltx_proof">
<h6 class="ltx_title ltx_runin ltx_font_italic ltx_title_proof">Solution.</h6>
<div id="S0.I1.i1.p2" class="ltx_para">
<p class="ltx_p">The claim follows from Fubini and independence:</p>
